Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case Called @ 9:05 AM: Attorney Ben Szilagyi in court.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant does not appear today.  SPD requests Court proceed without his client.  DA ready to proceed.  Court does not see a confrontational issue exists and counsel agree.  Per SPD:  Concedes to Daubert issue at this point in time.  DRE principles would be an issue for trial.  Per DA:  If the Court has sufficient information to rule without testimony, there would be no objection.  Requests record due to Def's nonappearance today for appellate purposes.  The Court:  Concerned over lack of Supreme Court meaningful direction as to Daubert.  This Court does its best with the case law that exists.  Five categories of 907.02 described.  Finds officer is a properly trained officer and refers to Ex B which articulates the adherence to the protocol undertaken.  Solely talking about the admissibility of the opinion and ability to interpret issues which were present and offer his opinion.  His opinion is admissible under 907.02.  Prevailing authorities again recited which establish admission in the State of Wisconsin as to the scientific principles.  Court believes HGN is the best barometer from which to measure DRE - conceptually aligned.  DRE testimony of Sgt Gunderson is admitted as per Ex B.   FPT Scheduled.  Final pre-trial scheduled for May 9, 2016 at 11:00 am.

Case called @ 2:51 p.m.  Defendant Erin M. Marinello in court with attorney Ben Szilagyi.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  MIL filed by both parties. DA Blader requesting a separate hearing to address the "Daubert" motion. Atty Szilagyi requesting an adjournment of the trial date due to unavailability of an expert witness. Statement by DA Blader. The Court will clear the trial and will schedule the motion hearing on that date to hear the "Daubert" motion. Jury Trial rescheduled to a date that conforms with the expert witness. DA Blader raises the issue of the jury instruction regarding the specific instruction that states what substance the defendant was under the influence of at the time of the offense. The Court advises counsel as to how the instruction will be crafted but will finalize the issue at the hearing on March 17th. DA Blader - another issue to be address is the mode of ingestion of the impairing substances. Statement by Atty Szilagyi - would like additional time to review that issue. The Court requests any subsequent motions to be filed by the parties by no later than March 4, 2016. DA Blader requesting a specific instruction be crafted regarding the playing of portions of the video of the stop. Statement by Atty Szilagy - only received the video this morning and has not had a opportunity to review at this point. Does not have any insight to offer at this time but does not foresee there being an issue. The Court does not believe that there will be an issue with the playing of only portions of the video of the stop to protect the defendant's rights. The parties stipulate as to the number of prior convictions to be stated should the defendant testify.The Court addresses the "Old Chief" stipulation by the defendant. The Court finds that that is a knowing, voluntary and intelligent "Old Chief" stipulation entered. The Court orders that a portion of the lab report discussed by the parties be redacted due to it's lack of relevance to the case.  Motion hearing scheduled for March 17, 2016 at 09:00 am.  Jury trial scheduled for June 15, 2016 at 08:00 am.
